V8 is Googleâ€™s open source high-performance JavaScript and WebAssembly engine, written in C++. It is used in Chrome and in Node.js, among others. It implements ECMAScript and WebAssembly, and runs on Windows, macOS, and Linux systems that use x64, IA-32, or ARM processors. V8 can be embedded into any C++ application.

68enum Condition : int {
69 overflow = 0,
70 no_overflow = 1,
71 below = 2,
72 above_equal = 3,
73 equal = 4,
74 not_equal = 5,
75 below_equal = 6,
76 above = 7,
77 negative = 8,
78 positive = 9,
79 parity_even = 10,
80 parity_odd = 11,
81 less = 12,
82 greater_equal = 13,
83 less_equal = 14,
84 greater = 15,
85
86 // aliases
87 carry = below,
88 not_carry = above_equal,
89 zero = equal,
90 not_zero = not_equal,
91 sign = negative,
92 not_sign = positive,
93
94 // Unified cross-platform condition names/aliases.
95 kEqual = equal,
96 kNotEqual = not_equal,
97 kLessThan = less,
98 kGreaterThan = greater,
99 kLessThanEqual = less_equal,
100 kGreaterThanEqual = greater_equal,
101 kUnsignedLessThan = below,
102 kUnsignedGreaterThan = above,
103 kUnsignedLessThanEqual = below_equal,
104 kUnsignedGreaterThanEqual = above_equal,
105 kOverflow = overflow,
106 kNoOverflow = no_overflow,
107 kZero = equal,
108 kNotZero = not_equal,

167enum ScaleFactor : int8_t {
168 times_1 = 0,
169 times_2 = 1,
170 times_4 = 2,
171 times_8 = 3,
172 times_int_size = times_4,
173
174 times_half_system_pointer_size = times_4,
175 times_system_pointer_size = times_8,
176 times_tagged_size = (kTaggedSize == 8) ? times_8 : times_4,
177 times_external_pointer_size = V8_ENABLE_SANDBOX_BOOL ? times_4 : times_8,

180class V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE Operand {
181 public:
182 struct LabelOperand {
183 // The first two fields are shared in {LabelOperand} and {MemoryOperand},
184 // but cannot be pulled out of the union, because otherwise the compiler
185 // introduces additional padding between them and the union, increasing the
186 // size unnecessarily.
187 bool is_label_operand = true;
188 uint8_t rex = 0; // REX prefix, always zero for label operands.
189
190 int8_t addend; // Used for rip + offset + addend operands.
191 Label* label;
192 };
193
194 struct MemoryOperand {
195 bool is_label_operand = false;
196 uint8_t rex = 0; // REX prefix.
197
198 // Register (1 byte) + SIB (0 or 1 byte) + displacement (0, 1, or 4 byte).
199 uint8_t buf[6] = {0};
200 // Number of bytes of buf in use.
201 // We must keep {len} and {buf} together for the compiler to elide the
202 // stack canary protection code.
203 size_t len = 1;
204 };
205
206 // Assert that the shared {is_label_operand} and {rex} fields have the same
207 // type and offset in both union variants.
208 static_assert(std::is_same<decltype(LabelOperand::is_label_operand),
209 decltype(MemoryOperand::is_label_operand)>::value);
210 static_assert(offsetof(LabelOperand, is_label_operand) ==
211 offsetof(MemoryOperand, is_label_operand));
212 static_assert(std::is_same<decltype(LabelOperand::rex),
213 decltype(MemoryOperand::rex)>::value);
214 static_assert(offsetof(LabelOperand, rex) == offsetof(MemoryOperand, rex));
215
216 static_assert(sizeof(MemoryOperand::len) == kSystemPointerSize,
217 "Length must have native word size to avoid spurious reloads "
218 "after writing it.");
219 static_assert(offsetof(MemoryOperand, len) % kSystemPointerSize == 0,
220 "Length must be aligned for fast access.");
221
222 // [base + disp/r]
223 V8_INLINE constexpr Operand(Register base, int32_t disp) {
224 if (base == rsp || base == r12) {
225 // SIB byte is needed to encode (rsp + offset) or (r12 + offset).
226 set_sib(times_1, rsp, base);
227 }
228
229 if (disp == 0 && base != rbp && base != r13) {
230 set_modrm(0, base);
231 } else if (is_int8(disp)) {
232 set_modrm(1, base);
233 set_disp8(disp);
234 } else {
235 set_modrm(2, base);
236 set_disp32(disp);
237 }
238 }
239
240 // [base + index*scale + disp/r]
241 V8_INLINE Operand(Register base, Register index, ScaleFactor scale,
242 int32_t disp) {
243 DCHECK(index != rsp);
244 set_sib(scale, index, base);
245 if (disp == 0 && base != rbp && base != r13) {
246 // This call to set_modrm doesn't overwrite the REX.B (or REX.X) bits
247 // possibly set by set_sib.
248 set_modrm(0, rsp);
249 } else if (is_int8(disp)) {
250 set_modrm(1, rsp);
251 set_disp8(disp);
252 } else {
253 set_modrm(2, rsp);
254 set_disp32(disp);
255 }
256 }
257
258 // [index*scale + disp/r]
259 V8_INLINE Operand(Register index, ScaleFactor scale, int32_t disp) {
260 DCHECK(index != rsp);
261 set_modrm(0, rsp);
262 set_sib(scale, index, rbp);
263 set_disp32(disp);
264 }
265
266 // Offset from existing memory operand.
267 // Offset is added to existing displacement as 32-bit signed values and
268 // this must not overflow.
269 Operand(Operand base, int32_t offset);
270
271 // [rip + disp/r]
272 V8_INLINE explicit Operand(Label* label, int addend = 0) {
273 DCHECK_NOT_NULL(label);
274 DCHECK(addend == 0 || (is_int8(addend) && label->is_bound()));
275 label_ = {};
276 label_.label = label;
277 label_.addend = addend;
278 }
279
280 Operand(const Operand&) V8_NOEXCEPT = default;
281 Operand& operator=(const Operand&) V8_NOEXCEPT = default;
282
283 V8_INLINE constexpr bool is_label_operand() const {
284 // Since this field is in the common initial sequence of {label_} and
285 // {memory_}, the access is valid regardless of the active union member.
286 return memory_.is_label_operand;
287 }
288
289 V8_INLINE constexpr uint8_t rex() const {
290 // Since both fields are in the common initial sequence of {label_} and
291 // {memory_}, the access is valid regardless of the active union member.
292 // Label operands always have a REX prefix of zero.
293 V8_ASSUME(!memory_.is_label_operand || memory_.rex == 0);
294 return memory_.rex;
295 }
296
297 V8_INLINE const MemoryOperand& memory() const {
298 DCHECK(!is_label_operand());
299 return memory_;
300 }
301
302 V8_INLINE const LabelOperand& label() const {
303 DCHECK(is_label_operand());
304 return label_;
305 }
306
307 // Checks whether either base or index register is the given register.
308 // Does not check the "reg" part of the Operand.
309 bool AddressUsesRegister(Register reg) const;
310
311 private:
312 V8_INLINE constexpr void set_modrm(int mod, Register rm_reg) {
313 DCHECK(!is_label_operand());
314 DCHECK(is_uint2(mod));
315 memory_.buf[0] = mod << 6 | rm_reg.low_bits();
316 // Set REX.B to the high bit of rm.code().
317 memory_.rex |= rm_reg.high_bit();
318 }
319
320 V8_INLINE constexpr void set_sib(ScaleFactor scale, Register index,
321 Register base) {
322 V8_ASSUME(memory_.len == 1);
323 DCHECK(is_uint2(scale));
324 // Use SIB with no index register only for base rsp or r12. Otherwise we
325 // would skip the SIB byte entirely.
326 DCHECK(index != rsp || base == rsp || base == r12);
327 memory_.buf[1] = (scale << 6) | (index.low_bits() << 3) | base.low_bits();
328 memory_.rex |= index.high_bit() << 1 | base.high_bit();
329 memory_.len = 2;
330 }
331
332 V8_INLINE constexpr void set_disp8(int disp) {
333 V8_ASSUME(memory_.len == 1 || memory_.len == 2);
334 DCHECK(is_int8(disp));
335 memory_.buf[memory_.len] = disp;
336 memory_.len += sizeof(int8_t);
337 }
338
339 V8_INLINE void set_disp32(int disp) {
340 V8_ASSUME(memory_.len == 1 || memory_.len == 2);
341 Address p = reinterpret_cast<Address>(&memory_.buf[memory_.len]);
342 WriteUnalignedValue(p, disp);
343 memory_.len += sizeof(int32_t);
344 }
345
346 union {
347 LabelOperand label_;
348 MemoryOperand memory_ = {};
349 };
350};

416// Partial Constant Pool
417// Different from complete constant pool (like arm does), partial constant pool
418// only takes effects for shareable constants in order to reduce code size.
419// Partial constant pool does not emit constant pool entries at the end of each
420// code object. Instead, it keeps the first shareable constant inlined in the
421// instructions and uses rip-relative memory loadings for the same constants in
422// subsequent instructions. These rip-relative memory loadings will target at
423// the position of the first inlined constant. For example:
424//
425// REX.W movq r10,0x7f9f75a32c20 ; 10 bytes
426// â€¦
427// REX.W movq r10,0x7f9f75a32c20 ; 10 bytes
428// â€¦
429//
430// turns into
431//
432// REX.W movq r10,0x7f9f75a32c20 ; 10 bytes
433// â€¦
434// REX.W movq r10,[rip+0xffffff96] ; 7 bytes
435// â€¦
436
437class ConstPool {
438 public:
439 explicit ConstPool(Assembler* assm) : assm_(assm) {}
440 // Returns true when partial constant pool is valid for this entry.
441 bool TryRecordEntry(intptr_t data, RelocInfo::Mode mode);
442 bool IsEmpty() const { return entries_.empty(); }
443
444 void PatchEntries();
445 // Discard any pending pool entries.
446 void Clear();
447
448 private:
449 // Adds a shared entry to entries_. Returns true if this is not the first time
450 // we add this entry, false otherwise.
451 bool AddSharedEntry(uint64_t data, int offset);
452
453 // Check if the instruction is a rip-relative move.
454 bool IsMoveRipRelative(Address instr);
455
456 Assembler* assm_;
457
458 // Values, pc offsets of entries.
459 std::multimap<uint64_t, int> entries_;
460
461 // Number of bytes taken up by the displacement of rip-relative addressing.
462 static constexpr int kRipRelativeDispSize = 4; // 32-bit displacement.
463 // Distance between the address of the displacement in the rip-relative move
464 // instruction and the head address of the instruction.
465 static constexpr int kMoveRipRelativeDispOffset =
466 3; // REX Opcode ModRM Displacement
467 // Distance between the address of the imm64 in the 'movq reg, imm64'
468 // instruction and the head address of the instruction.
469 static constexpr int kMoveImm64Offset = 2; // REX Opcode imm64
470 // A mask for rip-relative move instruction.
471 static constexpr uint32_t kMoveRipRelativeMask = 0x00C7FFFB;
472 // The bits for a rip-relative move instruction after mask.
473 static constexpr uint32_t kMoveRipRelativeInstr = 0x00058B48;
474};

476class V8_EXPORT_PRIVATE Assembler : public AssemblerBase {
477 private:
478 // We check before assembling an instruction that there is sufficient
479 // space to write an instruction and its relocation information.
480 // The relocation writer's position must be kGap bytes above the end of
481 // the generated instructions. This leaves enough space for the
482 // longest possible x64 instruction, 15 bytes, and the longest possible
483 // relocation information encoding, RelocInfoWriter::kMaxLength == 16.
484 // (There is a 15 byte limit on x64 instruction length that rules out some
485 // otherwise valid instructions.)
486 // This allows for a single, fast space check per instruction.
487 static constexpr int kGap = 32;
488 static_assert(AssemblerBase::kMinimalBufferSize >= 2 * kGap);
489
490 public:
491 // Create an assembler. Instructions and relocation information are emitted
492 // into a buffer, with the instructions starting from the beginning and the
493 // relocation information starting from the end of the buffer. See CodeDesc
494 // for a detailed comment on the layout (globals.h).
495 //
496 // If the provided buffer is nullptr, the assembler allocates and grows its
497 // own buffer. Otherwise it takes ownership of the provided buffer.
498 explicit Assembler(const AssemblerOptions&,
499 std::unique_ptr<AssemblerBuffer> = {});
500 // For compatibility with assemblers that require a zone.
501 Assembler(const MaybeAssemblerZone&, const AssemblerOptions& options,
502 std::unique_ptr<AssemblerBuffer> buffer = {})
503 : Assembler(options, std::move(buffer)) {}
504
505 ~Assembler() override = default;
506

511 void GetCode(LocalIsolate* isolate, CodeDesc* desc,
512 SafepointTableBuilderBase* safepoint_table_builder,
513 int handler_table_offset);
514
515 // Convenience wrapper for allocating with an Isolate.
516 void GetCode(Isolate* isolate, CodeDesc* desc);
517 // Convenience wrapper for code without safepoint or handler tables.
518 void GetCode(LocalIsolate* isolate, CodeDesc* desc) {

589 // ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
590 // InstructionStream generation
591 //
592 // Function names correspond one-to-one to x64 instruction mnemonics.
593 // Unless specified otherwise, instructions operate on 64-bit operands.
594 //
595 // If we need versions of an assembly instruction that operate on different
596 // width arguments, we add a single-letter suffix specifying the width.
597 // This is done for the following instructions: mov, cmp, inc, dec,
598 // add, sub, and test.
599 // There are no versions of these instructions without the suffix.
600 // - Instructions on 8-bit (byte) operands/registers have a trailing 'b'.
601 // - Instructions on 16-bit (word) operands/registers have a trailing 'w'.
602 // - Instructions on 32-bit (doubleword) operands/registers use 'l'.
603 // - Instructions on 64-bit (quadword) operands/registers use 'q'.
604 // - Instructions on operands/registers with pointer size use 'p'.
605
606#define DECLARE_INSTRUCTION(instruction) \
607 template <typename... Ps> \
608 void instruction##_tagged(Ps... ps) { \
609 emit_##instruction(ps..., kTaggedSize); \
610 } \
611 \
612 template <typename... Ps> \
613 void instruction##l(Ps... ps) { \
614 emit_##instruction(ps..., kInt32Size); \
615 } \
616 \
617 template <typename... Ps> \
618 void instruction##q(Ps... ps) { \
619 emit_##instruction(ps..., kInt64Size); \
620 }
621 ASSEMBLER_INSTRUCTION_LIST(DECLARE_INSTRUCTION)
622#undef DECLARE_INSTRUCTION
623
624 // Insert the smallest number of nop instructions
625 // possible to align the pc offset to a multiple
626 // of m, where m must be a power of 2.
627 void Align(int m);
628 // Insert the smallest number of zero bytes possible to align the pc offset
629 // to a mulitple of m. m must be a power of 2 (>= 2).
630 void DataAlign(int m);
631 void Nop(int bytes = 1);
632
633 // Intel CPUs with the Skylake microarchitecture suffer from a performance
634 // regression by the JCC erratum. To mitigate the performance impact, we align
635 // jcc instructions so that they will not cross or end at 32-byte boundaries.
636 // {inst_size} is the total size of the instructions which we will avoid to
637 // cross or end at the boundaries. For example, aaaabbbb is a fused jcc
638 // instructions, e.g., cmpq+jmp. In the fused case we have:
639 // ...aaaabbbbbb
640 // ^ ^
641 // | pc_offset + inst_size
642 // pc_offset
643 // And in the non-fused case:
644 // ...bbbb
645 // ^ ^
646 // | pc_offset + inst_size
647 // pc_offset
648 void AlignForJCCErratum(int inst_size);

1074 // Label operations & relative jumps (PPUM Appendix D)

1076 // Takes a branch opcode (cc) and a label (L) and generates
1077 // either a backward branch or a forward branch and links it
1078 // to the label fixup chain. Usage:
1079 //
1080 // Label L; // unbound label
1081 // j(cc, &L); // forward branch to unbound label
1082 // bind(&L); // bind label to the current pc
1083 // j(cc, &L); // backward branch to bound label
1084 // bind(&L); // illegal: a label may be bound only once
1085 //
1086 // Note: The same Label can be used for forward and backward branches
1087 // but it may be bound only once.

1506 void vpblendvb(XMMRegister dst, XMMRegister src1, XMMRegister src2,
1507 XMMRegister mask) {
1508 vinstr(0x4C, dst, src1, src2, k66, k0F3A, kW0);
1509 // The mask operand is encoded in bits[7:4] of the immediate byte.
1510 emit(mask.code() << 4);
1511 }

1515 // The mask operand is encoded in bits[7:4] of the immediate byte.
1516 emit(mask.code() << 4);
1517 }

2473 // Get the number of bytes available in the buffer.

2475 DCHECK_GE(reloc_info_writer.pos(), pc_);
2476 DCHECK_GE(kMaxInt, reloc_info_writer.pos() - pc_);
2477 return static_cast<int>(reloc_info_writer.pos() - pc_);

2513 template <typename T>
2514 static uint8_t* emit(uint8_t* __restrict pc, T t) {
2515 WriteUnalignedValue(reinterpret_cast<Address>(pc), t);
2516 return pc + sizeof(T);
2517 }

2543 // Emits a REX prefix that encodes a 64-bit operand size and
2544 // the top bit of the destination, index, and base register codes.
2545 // The high bit of reg is used for REX.R, the high bit of op's base
2546 // register is used for REX.B, and the high bit of op's index register
2547 // is used for REX.X. REX.W is set.
2548 inline void emit_rex_64(Register reg, Operand op);

2551 // Emits a REX prefix that encodes a 64-bit operand size and
2552 // the top bit of the register code.
2553 // The high bit of register is used for REX.B.
2554 // REX.W is set and REX.R and REX.X are clear.
2555 inline void emit_rex_64(Register rm_reg);
2556
2557 // Emits a REX prefix that encodes a 64-bit operand size and
2558 // the top bit of the index and base register codes.
2559 // The high bit of op's base register is used for REX.B, and the high
2560 // bit of op's index register is used for REX.X.
2561 // REX.W is set and REX.R clear.
2562 inline void emit_rex_64(Operand op);
2563
2564 // Emit a REX prefix that only sets REX.W to choose a 64-bit operand size.
2565 void emit_rex_64() { emit(0x48); }

2567 // High bit of reg goes to REX.R, high bit of rm_reg goes to REX.B.
2568 // REX.W is clear.

2570
2571 // The high bit of reg is used for REX.R, the high bit of op's base
2572 // register is used for REX.B, and the high bit of op's index register
2573 // is used for REX.X. REX.W is cleared.
2574 inline void emit_rex_32(Register reg, Operand op);

3141// Helper class that ensures that there is enough space for generating
3142// instructions and relocation information. The constructor makes
3143// sure that there is enough space and (in debug mode) the destructor
3144// checks that we did not generate too much.
3145class EnsureSpace {
3146 public:
3147 explicit V8_INLINE EnsureSpace(Assembler* assembler) : assembler_(assembler) {
3148 if (V8_UNLIKELY(assembler_->buffer_overflow())) assembler_->GrowBuffer();
3149#ifdef DEBUG
3150 space_before_ = assembler_->available_space();
3151#endif
3152 }
3153
3154#ifdef DEBUG
3155 ~EnsureSpace() {
3156 int bytes_generated = space_before_ - assembler_->available_space();
3157 DCHECK(bytes_generated < assembler_->kGap);
3158 }
3159#endif
3160
3161 private:
3162 Assembler* const assembler_;
3163#ifdef DEBUG
3164 int space_before_;
3165#endif
3166};
